AB  - Access within seaports can represent a weak link for logistics chain that include a maritime component. If the number of arriving trucks exceeds the processing capacity of the maritime terminals, cargo vehicles are blocked at the port access gates. The long queues of cargo vehicles that appear more and more often at the access gates area usually disrupt the activity of maritime terminals. Thus, there is a need to implement new intelligent technologies for traffic monitoring and control. The use of smart equipment helps the port administration in the classification and ranking of vehicles in relation to the term at which are accepted for processing by the maritime terminals. However, the implementation of these new technologies is difficult without a previous evaluation of the effects induced by them. The impact assessment induced by use of smart equipment was studied by the authors. For the specific case of a port in Romania, a discrete simulation model was developed. Based on it, a series of possible scenarios were studied. The obtained results can help any port administration in taking the decision to implement such smart equipment. © 2024 The Author(s).
