TI  - The PASSport Solution: A GNSS Approach Towards the Improvement of Safety and Security in Ports with Drone Surveillance
PY  - 2023
T2  - Proceedings of the 36th International Technical Meeting of the Satellite Division of the Institute of Navigation, ION GNSS+ 2023
SP  - 678
EP  - 695
DO  - 10.33012/2023.19326
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85184597740?origin=resultslist
AB  - Security in maritime ports is a complex problem given the particularity of these facilities, consisting of huge areas with many entry points operating constantly. This problem also involves risks that are linked to the use of technologies: the jamming and spoofing of GNSS signals can affect the operation of all GNSS-enabled vehicles operating in the port whereabouts (vessels and, potentially, drones). These issues have been identified by the maritime industry and, as a search for solutions, PASSport is a project that responds to port entities by extending situational awareness to improve safety and security in port areas. This is achieved through the combination of a fleet of drones with a network of RFI monitoring stations. The drone fleet is intended to provide an innovative operational support to the recognition, management and analysis of safety and security aspects of daily operations, introducing a real time dynamic surveillance solution. In order to ensure an accurate, secure and safe navigation, PASSport drones integrate GNSS receivers with dedicated capabilities to mitigate potential GNSS deficiencies in port operations, such as multipath or signal interferences. Given that most autopilots use GNSS information for navigation, the use of these capabilities is not only justified but necessary. These capabilities are, for accuracy, a PPP algorithm; for security, Galileo's OSNMA service; and for safety, the IBPL integrity approach. Off-board, additional support is introduced with the use of the interference detection system DINTEL/srx-10i. The purpose of this paper is to assess the functionalities of PPP, OSNMA and RFI monitoring in terms of robustness against spoofing attacks and accuracy of positioning obtained with authenticated navigation messages. These functionalities are validated with results obtained from different tests using real Signal-in-Space (SiS). These tests are performed in different European ports and locations, including Hamburg, Naples and Valencia. © 2023 Proceedings of the 36th International Technical Meeting of the Satellite Division of the Institute of Navigation, ION GNSS+ 2023. All rights reserved.
