AB  - The occurrence of sea fog leads to a sharp reduction in visibility, posing threats to maritime navigation and port operations. Existing visibility classification methods are predominantly developed for land scenarios, where the categorization of fog conditions remains coarse and is difficult to directly apply to the complex maritime environment. The scarcity of sea fog visibility datasets further exacerbates this challenge. To address these issues, this study proposes a fine-grained sea fog visibility classification network, M-ConvNeXt, designed for multilevel and real-time assessment in support of maritime safety. First, a frequency-domain perturbation strategy was developed to enhance sample diversity and improve model robustness. Then, an adaptive inverted residual block with channel attention was introduced to better extract fine-grained features of sea fog images across different categories. In addition, a maritime visibility image dataset covering six levels was constructed. Experimental results demonstrate that M-ConvNeXt achieves high accuracy and delivers robust performance in fine-grained sea fog visibility classification, with an average accuracy of 94.59%. This represents improvements of 8.06% over the baseline ConvNeXt-T, 6.83%, 5.97%, and 5.96% over CNN-based ResNeXt, ResNet50, and EfficientNet-B0, respectively, and 2.56% over Swin-Transformer. © 2001-2012 IEEE.
