AB  - Ensuring compliance with Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) regulations in construction is crucial to minimizing workplace injuries and fatalities. This research aims to monitor onsite workers and ensure compliance with PPE regulations to prevent violations that may result in serious accidents. The proposed solution evaluates the effectiveness of the latest YOLO version medium (YOLOv12) for real-time detection of PPE violations compared to older YOLO versions. A dataset of 2,047 annotated images was used to train various YOLO models using dual T4 GPUs on Kaggle. Optimization techniques such as hyperparameter tuning, data augmentation, and transfer learning were applied to enhance detection accuracy. The trained models were tested on original onsite videos, manually collected by the authors at the New Container Terminal of Damietta Port, Egypt. Model performance was assessed using evaluation metrics, including confusion matrices, F1-score, and precision-recall curves. Experimental results demonstrated that YOLOv12 achieved the highest precision, particularly in detecting small and distant objects, albeit with the longest training time. Conversely, YOLOv8 had the shortest training time while maintaining high accuracy. Additionally, this research introduces an automated reporting system that generates violation reports and sends real-time email alerts to safety engineers. This integration of the Internet of Things (IoT) enhances compliance monitoring, improves workplace safety, and ensures scalability for broader industrial applications.  © 2025 IEEE.
