AB  - Port portal cranes operate in complex and harsh environments for a long time, making Prognostics and Health Management (PHM) essential for ensuring their reliability and efficiency. Traditional status monitoring methods primarily utilize 3D visualization for equipment status display and motion simulation but lack precise modeling of operational conditions, limiting their effectiveness in comprehensive performance assessment. To address this challenge, this study develops a digital twin-based monitoring and simulation system of portal cranes for PHM. First, a digital space for the portal crane is constructed, and a virtual-physical interaction framework is established to achieve high-precision mapping between the physical entity and the virtual model. Second, a kinematic model for the luffing mechanism of the portal crane is developed using inverse kinematics principles to enhance simulation accuracy. Finally, a PHM-oriented monitoring and simulation system is implemented on the Unity3D platform, integrating six functional modules: twin model visualization, equipment status monitoring, structural health monitoring, environmental monitoring, operational parameter monitoring, and stress-strain simulation. The developed system enhances the comprehensiveness and accuracy of crane performance evaluation in PHM. This study provides a robust technical foundation for intelligent operation and maintenance, offering valuable insights for the development of smart and green ports. © 2025 IEEE.
