DO  - 10.2118/229863-MS
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033797632?origin=resultslist
AB  - This paper presents an ambitious and actionable framework for decarbonizing offshore logistics by integrating green bunkering technologies with AI-enhanced digital twin platforms. Targeting the transition from conventional IFO 380/180 CST fuels to zero-carbon alternatives such as green hydrogen, ammonia, and bio-methanol, the proposed system optimizes vessel routing, refueling schedules, and emissions compliance in real time. The methodology features a multilayered logistics optimization model embedded with life cycle emissions data and infrastructure constraints, simulating vessel operations across varying weather, load, and port conditions. AI-driven planning modules enable dynamic decision-making, identifying optimal fuel-switching strategies while forecasting demand with over 90% accuracy. Validated through offshore terminal simulations and supported by DNV and IMO benchmarks, the hybrid system achieved up to 45% reductions in GHG emissions and 30-50% cuts in SOx/NOx emissions. Hydrogen-powered vessels enabled zero-emission operation on short-range routes without incurring demurrage delays. Enhanced visibility across multi-port supply chains led to improved vessel utilization and maintenance predictability, ensuring compliance with IMO CII ratings and EU ETS requirements. This paper introduces a novel integration of green bunkering with smart logistics for the petroleum sector-merging emissions tracking, AI optimization, and infrastructure-aware bunkering into a scalable, real-world decarbonization strategy. The result is a resilient offshore logistics model capable of supporting global energy transition goals while maintaining operational performance and regulatory alignment. Copyright © 2025, Society of Petroleum Engineers.
