TI  - Drivers of digital twin adoption in smart ports: a systematic review of empirical evidence
PY  - 2026
T2  - Australian Journal of Maritime and Ocean Affairs
DO  - 10.1080/18366503.2026.2644703
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105033367391?origin=resultslist
AB  - Digital Twin (DT) technology is increasingly central to smart port transformation; however, the drivers behind its adoption remain unclear. This systematic review analysed 30 publications to identify and classify the key factors motivating DT adoption in global smart ports. Through structured screening and qualitative content analysis, 27 drivers were extracted and grouped into five categories: operational performance and efficiency, prediction and data-driven decision-making, security and risk management, energy optimization and decarbonization, and infrastructure and asset management. The results indicate that operational efficiency is the dominant driver, with China and Europe leading DT implementation. This study contributes a consolidated framework of DT adoption drivers, offering a reference for practitioners and policymakers planning digitalization initiatives. The study is limited by its reliance on published academic sources; therefore, future research should validate the alignment of these drivers with industry practices and investigate barriers affecting DT deployment in real-world port settings. © 2026 Informa UK Limited, trading as Taylor & Francis Group.
