AB  - As large ships become increasingly common in global maritime transportation, the berthing process faces greater challenges in terms of spatial constraints, environmental disturbances, and safety requirements. Under such conditions, real-time and accurate acquisition of ship berthing attitude is essential for ensuring berthing safety, reducing collision risks, and enabling intelligent port operations. In large ship berthing operations, distance measurements are typically obtained manual observation or laser rangefinders; however, these approaches are limited in their ability to comprehensively capture the subtle dynamic movements of the bow and stern during the berthing process. To address the issue of insufficient accuracy and robustness in obtaining real-time ship attitude under noisy marine environmental conditions, first, this study enhances the conventional RANSAC algorithm by incorporating curvature information into a redesigned energy function. This enhancement improves the accuracy of fitting the main surface plane of the ship. Then, we introduce a geometric offset rule to generate candidate points between the bow and stern, aiming to enhance the stability of attitude estimation and reduce the impact of noise and incomplete local point cloud data. Finally, Kalman Filtering (KF) is integrated with Bayesian Online Change Point Detection (BOCPD) to achieve smooth and accurate estimation of ship position and velocity while adaptively detecting sudden changes under noisy conditions. Both simulation and tank experiments demonstrate that the proposed method can reliably estimate berthing angle, offshore distance, and berthing velocity under high-noise point cloud conditions. It also exhibits strong capabilities in change-point detection and attitude estimation accuracy, verifying the robustness and practicality of the algorithm. This study provides a real-time and robust technical solution for autonomous berthing and safety monitoring of large ships in constrained waterways or complex port basins, supporting the development of smart ports and the automation of maritime transportation. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.
