TI  - Multi-period modeling of floating production storage and offloading dock mooring line tensions using TimesNet-based deep learning framework
PY  - 2026
T2  - Ocean Engineering
VL  - 353
C7  - 124651
DO  - 10.1016/j.oceaneng.2026.124651
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105035264100?origin=resultslist
AB  - The safety and stability of dock mooring systems for Floating Production Storage and Offloading (FPSO) vessels are critical, as they directly impact dock structural integrity and cargo loading/unloading operations. However, existing research on mooring dynamics in complex marine environments faces several challenges, including inadequate multi-periodicity modeling, neglect of transient impact loads, and limited data fidelity. These challenges mainly arise from the scarcity of long-term field measurements and the uncertainty of environmental conditions, rather than from the limitations of numerical modeling itself. In this study, a high-fidelity dynamic mooring model based on ANSYS-AQWA—calibrated against the real configuration of the terminal project—is employed to generate reliable reference data for training and benchmarking of machine learning models. To address these issues, this study proposes a prediction model based on TimesNet, designed to explicitly capture the multi-periodic characteristics and dynamic coupling effects of mooring tension. A fully coupled numerical model of the FPSO dock mooring system is developed using ANSYS-AQWA (Advanced Quadrature Wave Analysis), generating a high-fidelity dataset that accounts for the combined effects of wind, waves, and currents. The prediction performance of six mainstream models—including Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM), Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (BiLSTM), and Complete Ensemble Empirical Mode Decomposition with Adaptive Noise-Convolutional Neural Networks-LSTM-Attention (CEEMDAN-CNN-LSTM-AT) is systematically compared. Results indicate that the TimesNet model outperforms others in ultra-short-term prediction (with a time step of 9s), achieving an R2 value of 0.982 for bow mooring line tension forecasting. Under high-tide conditions, increased mooring line tension leads to greater nonlinearity and fluctuation, resulting in higher prediction errors compared to low-tide conditions. Despite larger load fluctuations in single cables within the operational mooring layout, the model maintains high predictive accuracy. The findings of this study provide theoretical support for the adaptive control of FPSO dock mooring winches and preventive maintenance strategies while laying the groundwork for the development of digital twin systems. © 2026 Elsevier Ltd. All rights are reserved, including those for text and data mining, AI training, and similar technologies.
