VL  - 1
SP  - 683
EP  - 689
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/84983033967?origin=resultslist
AB  - In 2009, the Port Authority collaborated with EPA Region 2 and other partners to develop a plan, known as the Clean Air Strategy, to reduce emissions by at least 3-5%/yr despite its projected growth. Communities near the Port, including neighborhoods in Newark, Elizabeth, Jersey City, Staten Island, and Brooklyn may benefit from continued emission reductions, potentially decreasing concerns over disproportionate burden of exposure to air pollution from proximate sources related to port activities. One promising emerging strategy is to conduct high time-resolution measurements coupled with a local scale modeling approach known as Nonparametric Trajectory Analysis (NTA). To maximize utilizing this approach for application near the Port, the Region 2 Port-area Investigation of Emissions Reduction (R2PIER) air monitoring site was situated south of the main container terminals of the Port of New York and New Jersey in the summer of 2012. The R2PIER project involves a long-term, high-time resolution air measurement and data-driven modeling approach to maximize the amount of information gained from a single monitoring location. Preliminary application of the NTA model for time periods before and after hurricane Sandy demonstrated the ability of the measurement-model approach to observe trends in surrounding source emissions.
