TI  - Quality Metocean Data - Methods to Improve Real-Time Outcomes
PY  - 2023
T2  - Australasian Coasts and Ports 2023 Conference
SP  - 80
EP  - 85
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85183579456?origin=resultslist
AB  - While ports around the world try to accommodate newer and larger vessels, operating margins have become narrower as the growth rate of ports has not matched the same level of growth in vessel dimensions as discussed in PIANC Report N 117 - Use of Hydro/Meteo Information for Port Access and Operations (2012). Therefore, decision making aided by good quality real-time environmental data is key in the pursuit of increased port safety and productivity. With an increase in extreme weather events due to climate change, there is a heightened need to accurately predict future conditions. This serves to reduce delays due to adverse weather while ensuring the safety of port operations and personnel. While there are a lot of advancements being made in weather forecasting due to the introduction of continuous improvement of models, Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Learning (ML), and access to more powerful computation, the quality of a forecast is still limited by the quality of the real-time data that feeds into the model. This highlights the need for standards and systems that ensure reliability and quality control of real-time data. This paper aims to explore the importance of quality real-time metocean data in port operations, and the industry best practice methods used to assess real-time data. An overview of OMC International's use of the state-of-the-art Quality Assurance/Quality Control of Real-Time Oceanographic Data (QARTOD) testing framework will be provided. The automated QARTOD tests will be explored in the form of case studies, with an emphasis on operational use at OMC International (OMC). System redundancies such as alerting and visual monitoring will be discussed. © 2023 Australasian Coasts and Ports 2023 Conference. All Rights Reserved.
